JOHANNESBURG The Competition Commission on Monday said it filed with the Competition Tribunal a settlement agreement reached with Citibank N.A. for being part of the forex trading cartel. The Commission found that from at least 2007, Citibank N.A. and its competitors had a general agreement to collude on prices for bids, offers and bid-offer spreads for the spot trades in relation to currency trading involving US Dollar / Rand currency pair, the commission said in a statement.The commission said it had found that Citibank N.A. and its competitors manipulated the price of bids and offers through agreements to refrain from trading and creating fictitious bids and offers at particular times.READ: Tough sanctions called for colluding banks Citibank N.A. will pay an administrative penalty of R69,500,860. This figure does not exceed 10 percent of Citibank N.A. s annual turnover in the Republic of South Africa. Citibank N.A. undertook to cooperate with the Commission and avail witnesses to assist the prosecution of the other banks that colluded in this matter, the commission said. This settlement was done to encourage speedy settlement and full disclosure to strengthen the evidence for prosecution of the other banks, said the Commissioner, Tembinkosi Bonakele.Last week, the Competition Commission referred a collusion case to the tribunal for prosecution against 17 local and international banks.Tough sanctions have been called for the banks found guilty of colluding to fix the price of the rand.eNCA